- 'Crème de la crème' refers to the best of something; 
- The model performance metrics (accuracy, F1 score, recall, precision) and fairness metrics (average absolute odds differences, between all groups Theil index) are commonly used to evaluate machine learning models; 
- The query filters models trained between '2022-01-01' and '2022-12-31', which indicates that it only considers models from the year 2022.

; The overall performance of a model is determined by its average accuracy, F1 score, and balanced accuracy; 
; Fairness metrics include the average absolute odds difference and Theil index for both race and sex, which measure the difference in model performance across different demographic groups; 
; Bias metrics include the average disparate impact ratio and statistical parity difference, which measure the difference in model performance between different demographic groups.

sql:
SELECT AVG(md.value) AS average_group_value
FROM model_demographics md
JOIN demographic_groups dg ON md.group_id = dg.group_id;

SELECT disparate_impact_ratio
FROM bias_metrics
WHERE evaluation_date < '2022-02-01';

SELECT model_id, AVG(disparate_impact_ratio) AS avg_disparate_impact_ratio
FROM bias_metrics
GROUP BY model_id;
